  "prompt": "Why didn't PM Narendra Modi end reservation?",
  "response": "Narendra Modi has not ended reservation in India for several complex reasons:\n\n1. Political considerations\n- Reservations have strong political support\n- Removing them could lead to significant electoral backlash\n- Provides social justice to historically marginalized communities\n\n2. Constitutional provisions\n- Article 15 and 16 of the Indian Constitution guarantee reservation\n- Reservations are legally protected and deeply embedded in the system\n\n3. Social equity concerns\n- Reservation aims to address historical discrimination\n- Many communities still face socio-economic challenges\n- Supports representation of marginalized groups\n\n4. Public sentiment\n- Large sections of society support reservation policy\n- Strong opposition to its complete removal\n- Seen as a tool for social mobility\n\n5. BJP's political strategy\n- Modi's party recognizes reservation's political sensitivity\n- Has instead focused on expanding reservation's scope\n- Introduced 10% reservation for economically weaker sections\n\n6. Practical implementation challenges\n- Sudden removal would create massive social disruption\n- Complex legal and administrative barriers\n\nWhile Modi has not ended reservations, his government has modified and expanded the policy, reflecting a nuanced approach to this sensitive issue.\n\nThese factors explain why complete abolition of reservations remains unlikely under his leadership.",
